{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}} __NOTOC__ {{Infobox project | name = Older People for Older People | logo = O4O logo.png | website = {{URL|www.o4os.eu}} | commercial = No | type = [[Community building]] | location = {{ubl|[[Scotland]]|[[Finland]]|[[Greenland]]|[[Northern Ireland]]|[[Sweden]]}}<ref name="europa video" /> | owner = Northern Periphery Programme | mission_statement = independent living{{,}}active communities{{,}}flexible services | date_of_establishment = 2008 | funding = {{ubl|€2 125 530 (total)|€1 183 997 (EU contribution)}}<ref name="europa mobilising" /> }} '''Older People for Older People''' (or '''O4O''') was a project aimed to provide a greater degree of independence to the elderly whom were located in non-urban areas.<ref>{{cite web|title=Older People for Older People|url=http://www.understandingglasgow.com/asset_based_approaches/older_people_for_older_people_o40|website=Understanding Glasglow|publisher=Th Glasglow Indicator Project|accessdate=13 April 2017}}</ref>
The project was a winner at the Regions for Economic Change Conference in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=O4O Project wins RegioStars 2012 Awards|url=http://www.northernperiphery.eu/en/newsletter/show/&tid=105|website=Northern Periphery Program|publisher=European Regional Development Fund|accessdate=13 April 2017}}</ref>
== History ==
With the intent to focus on what the elderly could provide for a community, and recognize their capabilities,<ref name="o4os" /> the project investigated the means of using [[community building]] to facilitate the provision of services available to those people of [[old age]]. It used older people's skills to assist other older people,<ref name="ruralgateway" /> delaying the times at which they move out of their own homes.<ref name="pressandjournal 2010" /> It was part-financed by the [[European Regional Development Fund]] through the Northern Periphery Programme and covered rural areas of [[Scotland]], [[Finland]], [[Greenland]], [[Northern Ireland]] and [[Sweden]].<ref name="europa video" /> It ran from 2008<ref name="ruralgateway" /> to 2013.<ref name="hie 2012" /> At the end of the project, some services developed under it continued to be provided.<ref name="northernperiphery 2012" />
The project was supported by the [[University of the Highlands and Islands]], the [[University of Aberdeen]] and the [[Highlands and Islands Enterprise]].<ref name="hie 2012" /> The project was shortlisted for the RegioStars awards in December 2011<ref name="centreforhealthscience 2011" /> and announced as winner at the Regions for Economic Change Conference in 2012.<ref name="hie 2012" />
== Outcomes ==
One project outcome was the development of a toolkit to help others create their own O4O projects. Some example outcomes which were developed are [[community transport]], [[supported housing]], [[self-sufficiency]] via a luncheon club using shared local produce, [[volunteering]] and schemes for friendship and helping.<ref name="europa mobilising" /><ref name="o4os" /> {{Clear}}
